output:
The issue with your solution is that it is not correctly checking for the maximum length substring that is common in both the first and second word. The current approach is to check for each character in the second word if it exists in the first word and then increment the answer. This will not work as it does not ensure that the characters are in the same order in both words.

To solve this problem, you can use dynamic programming. Create a 2D array dp of size (N+1) x (M+1) where N and M are the lengths of the first and second word respectively. The value of dp[i][j] will store the length of the longest common substring of the first i characters of the first word and the first j characters of the second word.

The base cases are dp[0][0] = 0, dp[i][0] = 0 and dp[0][j] = 0.

The recurrence relation is dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1 if first[i-1] == second[j-1] else dp[i-1][j].

Finally, the answer will be the maximum value in the dp array.

Here is the updated code:
```
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    long long n, m;
    cin >> n >> m;
    vector<long long> first(n), second(m);
    for (long long i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        cin >> first[i];
    }
    for (long long i = 0; i < m; i++) {
        cin >> second[i];
    }
    vector<vector<long long>> dp(n+1, vector<long long>(m+1, 0));
    for (long long i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
        for (long long j = 1; j <= m; j++) {
            if (first[i-1] == second[j-1]) {
                dp[i][j] = dp[i-1][j-1] + 1;
            } else {
                dp[i][j] = max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]);
            }
        }
    }
    cout << dp[n][m] << endl;
    return 0;
}
```
This should work for all test cases.

